reviews.text: One of the best galleries I’ve been to so far in Dublin. It’s free to enter, educational and the artifacts are very well displayed. Will definitely be visiting again and hopefully will be able to see the roof garden which everyone keeps raving about :)

This is a great hidden gem in Dublin. I feel like many people don’t understand the importance of Chester Beatty in bringing the oriental to the European eye. The staff is extremely knowledgeable, and float around so all you have to do is ask a question and they are at your service. Many rooms to look through and floors to explore. Went to the rooftop garden in January and it was gorgeous to see the city, and I can’t imagine how beautiful it would be in the spring!

Free to enter and should definitely be on anyone's list who loves history and culture. The Bible exhibition on the top floor was amazing with papyri dating back to shortly after the time of the apostles. Easy to guide yourself around the exhibits.

I really knew nothing about Chester Beatty or the library before this visit, but it was a hidden treasure. It's free to enter, so that's a plus, but there are a ton of amazing and rare collections in this place! You can spend as much time in the library as you want, and there's a cafeteria, if you're hungry. The staff is so gracious and helpful, and learning the story of Chester Beatty was definitely worth the visit.

This is a really cool place! I was expecting a regular library with stacks of books everywhere but it's more like a museum, a lot more like a museum, and gives lots of history about different religious and cultural texts and books. The Asian history section was definitely my favourite!

Loved the tour there. Our guide was full of information that is not readily found in the brochures. The grounds are well kept and provide a nice walk full of sculptures, both old and modern. The castle is luxurious with details at every turn. The restoration and maintenance of the Castle and the exhibits are extraordinary. Plan to spend a couple of hours exploring everything.

Great place to visit. Sense of history is almost palpable. You can simply walk the ground & small walled garden for free. Or pay to tour the inside. I recommend both. There's also a cafe within the castle, great cakes.

Absolutely beautiful place. Highly recommend paying for the tour and experience that! The guides are extremely knowledgeable and friendly. They can answer any questions you may have and do so with a smile. The atmosphere is very historical and you can learn so much about Irish history. Highly recommend a visit!!!

The castle is a great visit. Loved the courtyard and the artifacts you can see inside. The whole deal was quaint and historic. I'd suggest a tour. We didn't take one but hearing what the guides say passing by made it sound like a great experience.

Located in the heart of Dublin, the Dublin Castle was a important British stronghold for more than 700 years, but now it´s the major Irish Government building and also one of the most famous tourist place in Dublin. It's a must to go in the city to learn more about the local history and you can visit for free every first Wednesday of the month.

Awesome detailed and thorough exhibit on the Easter Rising. Great to see a bit of Irish history at this museum. Well laid-out with lots of interactive spots too - even as an adult I greatly enjoyed the mail sorting game. Love the "what do you think?" parts of the exhibit as well. A quieter but lovely place to visit!

Quick and Wonderful Staff, from International Post to Local. A bit pricey for the international packages, so get your own boxes somewhere else. They got DHL as well and that's Handy. I love there Displays during the holidays inside and out and the Museum inside is worth a look. Loads of History here.

Used to be the best service for parcel delivery, now they've stopped their collection service with no notice and are crippling the prices. Many other companies out there that will collect packages for the same or far less.

I have never seen a post office like this before in my life...in a very good way!! This is one of the best historical attractions in Dublin.

The exterior architecture is simply breathtaking. I was so mesmerized i forgot to even take a pictire of the exterior! Lol. It seems here in Dublin a post office offers so many services besides just mailing letters and packages (buying stamps for stamp collections, bills...)! 

This post office was packed however the lines do move very fast and efficiently. There's a cafe, museum, and store as well.

When we visited, it was beautifully decorated for Christmas and there was a fundraiser with living singing. It was simply magical.

In 1916, the GPO Building was at the centre of the Easter Uprising. The GPO building has of course been restored from the result of the battle. The striking building is a fine example of Georgian architecture. The neo-classical front of the building has six beautiful Ionic columns, topped with a pediment where stands statues of Mercury, Fidelity on the right, and Hibernia in the centre, resting on her spear and holding a harp. The impressive exterior is matched by a restored interior with plenty of brass and wood details.

The GPO building also houses an exhibition of the Easter Uprising. There's a lot of information about the event and I thought very impressive in the depth of the information provided. The highlight of the exhibition is probably the film re-enacting GPO's use as the command centre of the uprising, and the video interviews with various historians analysing the result of the uprising. Good to see an exhibition that doesn't try to dumb down the information in the interest of accessibility.

Well worth a visit if in Dublin.

Well laid-out with lots of interactive spots too - even as an adult I greatly enjoyed the mail sorting game. Love the "what do you think?" parts of the exhibit as well. A quieter but lovely place to visit!

It was great! I hadn't expected a cemetery to be a place that you could do so much and see so much.
The Botanical gardens at the rear of the cemetery are well worth a visit and so is the museum. 
All the staff are very knowledgeable and incredibly helpful.
When you've had your full and are ready for a sit down the restaurant serves very good food and delicious homemade cakes.
The day has been excellent.
We went on the 'Dead Interesting' Tour and Warren was our guide. We thoroughly enjoyed it and Warren was very informative and knowledgeable and very friendly. I'd highly recommend this Tour.
Amazing experience. A must see in Dublin.. even with a big crowd we still managed to hear.  Nialls (history teacher)  knowledge was outstanding!!

Myself and my Wife Breda had the most amazing experience today in this Cemetery. The history attached to it is just mind blowing. Our guide Ariel gave us the most passionate 90 minute speech, he was amazing, the tour was  amazing, we have to go back. Soon. Thanks Ariel.

Really well maintained cemetery. Getting a tour guide is a must, so much Irish history associated with people buried here. On a clear day the views from the tower are worth a see too. Would recommend a pint in the Gravediggers pub afterwards.
stayed at a Barge here great security, no issues at all highly recommend
Waterways Ireland are responsibile for the management, maintenance, development and restoration of inland navigable waterways principally for recreational purposes.
Loved the centre.Modern,bright,quiet with last generation facilities.Very friendly staff.Opened Saturdays.They have temporary exhibitions inside.Ready to go about history
Very limited exhibit...in and out in a short time
Had more staff than visitors. Models and displays are limited. Would suit school tour though.

This is a great meeting spot in Ireland.  This is a monument to the girl in the Irish song playing all over Ireland.   This song seems far more popular here than Danny Boy.  The statue was brown, but as you can see when viewing it, certain parts have been worn to a lighter gold due to frequent touching and rubbing.

To be honest there is so much charm in downtown Dublin and the Molly Malone statue and all the rest of the statues help create that charm. This review has to touch the other points of interest near the statue. There are tons of shops and places to eat and there were so many I doubt I could focus on one. But near the statue there is a plethora of activities you can engage in.

Can't come to Dublin and not see the Molly Malone statue. She is the symbol of Dublin and has excellent breasts.

Tourists can keep their hand of her. Very attractive women/statue

Nearby you will find various places to eat ranging from traditional Irish food to Lebanese cuisine. 

Also trinity college is just round the corner which is a must see. Particularly the long room.

100 recommend visiting

The statue is located is Suffolk street, Dublin 2 and dates from 1988. Molly is life-size and made of bronze. It is said that touching Molly’s breasts will bring you good fortune and guarantee you to return to Dublin. Even tough Molly is fictional character, the legend that surrounds her is marvellously fun. Do check out YouTube and listen to the song, as it is well-known all across Ireland.

Been a while since I went to see this iconic statue after it's move from previous location. Current place is a lot better than the previous one as the area is nice. Usually it's busy with so many tourists taking photos

Turned up today at opening time. They were closed. Their security staff had not bothered to turn up. Told to return at half past. I did. Staff told me to go away, in a manner that was very unfriendly and rude. As if I were a hindrance, coming to see the museum. Gave one star, as it might be a nice museum. Staff don't care enough to turn up so I didn't see the inside.
Great house with great work within the walls, you will have to spend around 2/3 hours to read and look at everything. However a quick trip is possible
Worth a quick visit if you are in the area and have some extra cash. Not fancy or big.
Great museum. Not big but interesting and in a beautiful house

This is a scoring between a 3.5 and 4. 
Museum is small correct, but it's full on. Expect to spend a good amount of time there. Loads to read, loads to absorb and listen too. 
My lower scoring is related to how the collection is arranged. There is relatively no information on the 1st floor. There is a huge gap on Irish women writers (very few are mentioned).
The ground floor has a coffee shop in the back but there was poor signage. The most disappointing moment was the museum shop. Not sure how it is as it was closed on my visit with no information if it was permanent or just staff needed elsewhere. 
Would like to revisit and change my review in a future time.
Very difficult to find. Poor facilities.
We had a yoga session here and it felt like an under renovation place.
Great contemporary gallery
the VERY best
i love art , its Flamboyant

If you’re lucky enough to get Ray as your tour guide then you’re in for an awesome tour. It’s small but extremely interesting. We had a great time. You’re able to see the conditions under which the Irish emigrated from Ireland to various countries.
A truly great experience with a passionate guide who knows how to captivate his audience. Went there with a group of French students. They understood  him perfectly.

We really enjoyed this tour. It lasted around 45 minutes during which time you are taken onto the ship and told of the ship's history, mainly relating to it transporting passengers across the Atlantic during the Irish potato famine. You get a chance to explore the deck and below deck and hear about the ship's history as well as information about the passengers and crew. Tickets can be bought at the kiosk beside the ship and the tours begin on the hour. Our tickets cost €10.50 per adult and we considered it money well spent. Check it out if you're in the area

Amazing tour, with a lot of history explained by the guides. Even if you don't care about the ship itself but do care about the history of emigration from Ireland, you will enjoy this tour.

If you are interested in the topic and only have time to visit either EPIC or the Jeanie Johnston, pick the Jeanie Johnston.

I picked the last your of the day.  I ended up with a one on one your with a very knowledgeable docent.  I thoroughly enjoyed it, and would recommend it to others.  A great empathy exercise to better understand what the people endured in search for a better life.

Amazing. Simply beautiful art, in a variety of media. The stained glass room is a must see. Huge variety of contemporary and classical painting and sculpture. Definitely too much for a single day, repeat visits recommended. Free admission with recommend donation is hard to beat too. The kids' activity stuff is great fun too.

I love coming to the National Gallery. It's free/by donation with some special exhibits charging a small fee (these rotate). I love the Irish art on the first floor. It's a relaxing place to wander around.

There's a cafe (that serves lunch in addition to coffee and such) and a gift shop. The shop has a lot of postcards, some greeting cards, art books and supplies, children's toys,  jewelry, ties and more. Definitely recommend a visit to this gallery.

Love the new wing! The large room with the double staircase is amazing. Great place to see Irish art and some pieces by the classic European painters. Went to see Canaletto exhibition recently and it was very well laid out and the audio guides were great too. Highly recommend for a rainy day and of those there are plenty in Dublin!

First of all it's free so I didn't expect much but got surprised. The building itself is spectacular architecture wise. The paintings presented are few but awesome. The descriptions of the paintings are catching and very informative. Staff looks friendly hadn't a talk with them so can't say anything else about them. All in all I had a good 1 1/2 hour here!

I spent a Sunday afternoon here and it was brilliant. I'm far from an art connoisseur, so the descriptions beside each painting and sculpture were very helpful and insightful.

The gallery itself is well designed and pleasant to walk through, and the staff are friendly. My only regret is visiting on a warm sunny afternoon, so it was quite warm and quite busy inside, but I still enjoyed my visit and will definitely return.

It is a museum that contains diverse exhibits from the Irish in various armies around the world to exhibits on silverware. As an adult it is quite interesting to see Irish history and seeing the historic ship the Asgard was very interesting for me. For kids they see a big boat and there are parts of the museum they get to handle which kids like. The museum could do with some more child friendly parts to the museum. There is a temporary exhibit at the moment on dinosaurs and early bird evolution which of course is always a favourite for adults and kids alike.

I didn't have many expectations of this entry in Dublin's collection of free museums (that's a reflection on me, not the museum!), but ended up being pleasantly surprised. 

Much more than a collection of textiles, the museum has features on objects collected by Irish persons of note from around the world (including some exquisite Japanese prints), as well as a feature on Ireland's evolving currency and, at the time of my visit, a very disturbing piece about the Magdalene laundries - good to acknowledge this kind of thing, no matter how difficult a subject matter this may be.

The museum also had a sizable military history piece going on when I visited, but much to my regret I ran out of time and had to move on.

Plenty of stuff to see in a well preserved big building that used to be barracks. Mainly clothing and furniture on display but also has a significant military history area.

Some exhibitions could benefit from a bit more detail but overall it has good information.

And you can't argue with the price: it's free!
You need a good full day to fully appreciate your visit, even then you will not have seen everything. Brilliant, and no admission charge.
Great museum, with a spacious and photogenic courtyard area. Some nice displays, particularly on the 1916 rising. Well worth a visit, and it has free entry.

This historic cafe is a must do while in Dublin. The atmosphere is great the food fresh and well prepared and the staff on on it! The breakfast/brunch options seemed more appealing. Lived getting to see the bakers at work downstairs. It's amazing to thinks it's over 180 years old,no surprise it's still going strong with the quality of food and service. I can't wait for my next visit!

A charming and original place. I love the vibes and the environment, but also the service has always been efficient. I know it can get really busy but me and my friends have always been lucky since we've always managed to get some seats fast. The cake are delicious, if you want to enjoy some elaborated pastries with a tasty coffee i would recommend going there. The opera cake and the eclair are must-try

I really love this place, they have the best carrot cake what I ever had. Actually I love the presentation of the hot chocolate too.
The building is refurbished and is new now, that give you a very good place to stay and relax with yourself or friends. Is busy on weekends but during the week is just perfect.

Seated straight away upstairs, then took Twenty minutes or more to place our order. We ordered coffees, hot chocolate and cakes and it took a long time to arrive. Very slow service. Hot chocolate was lovely as were the cakes but, as expected, expensive. Coffee was fine but there is much better around the corner

I’ve been here a number of times now and the food is lovely and they definitely make the best chai latte ever. The staff are run off their feet from the time the doors open. Despite this they are always very friendly, chatty and helpful. 

I highly recommend here for a breakfast or cake and suggest you take the time to admire the classic tea room decor.

A couple of weeks back I did have a bad experience, however customer service were very good in dealing with it to ensure that they can provide the best experience for every customer.

Amazing chocolates and sweeties and good quality of coffee and hot drinks!!it gets extremely busy during weekends.. So limited chances of finding a table. However there's a  takeaway option. Gift options also available,although a bit overpriced.
great coffee and you always get a free chocolate of your choice with your coffe. this cafe has seating inside and outside and also a good selection of chocolate boxes to buy.
Busy but delicious coffee. Good to take away and drink while you explore. Free piece of chocolate with your drink.
Top of the luxury cafes. Nicer than the other chains/ franchises
Hot chocolate extremely sweet, as were the chocolates themselves.
vegan food, yeah, very delicious. I often meet people here to talk. I look forward to a return visit. This place has a cool feel to it. Ambience reminds me of Colorado Springs area.

A total safe haven for plant-based people. Feels like a commune. No frills vegan Indian restaurant with all-you-can-eat buffet for $8. Tons of veggies, leafy greens and gluten free foods. We dined in due to heavy rain. Can't wait to sit on their front patio and enjoy their baked goods with a beverage.
Great location for quality Vegan food. Got there near seven, it wasn't very crowded. The service was very welcoming and observant.
Good location for vegan food. The service here is above par. The bill was good for how much you get. Menu is similar to a restaurant in El Paso I liked.
My fav location for delicious Vegan food. Went there on a Saturday. The place has a good atmosphere.

Found this cafe by chance. Looked very inviting. Happy that I went in. The breakfast was tasty and the staff were very pleasant. Definitely recommend it for anyone looking to have a nice relaxing breakfast and coffee. Thanks!

The cafe is clean and comfortable once sat down. The staff are polite and busy workers. The place is small so once they get a group things slow down but this happens in lots of places. The main reason for the the low star rating is that on the breakfast menu there was only one veggie option  - porridge and toast. There should be a veggie fry as this would be a simple solution - hash browns, beans, tomato, fried bread etc. There were no pancakes either. I would say meat eaters would add one star.
Lovely food at a reasonable price. Very friendly staff. Highly recommended.
Very nice place with good coffee and very nice breakfast options. Staff are really friendly and accommodating. Very good to have breakfast when visiting Dublin
Always enjoy eating here, lovely staff and the food is great

Such a great place to grab a quick meal with friends. Came and got my first original fish and chips and was not let down by the review my friend gave that i was visiting. The fish was absolutely unbeatable. They fried it perfectly golden and crispy.  The chips were fantastic, throw some of the vinegar and salt on them to be transported to another world. Definitely worth checking out.
The chips where good but the fish was less so. The batter was a bit soggy. Have had better meals in the past here so wouldn't be in a rush back.

This is one of Dublins great institution and for fish and chips it's up there amongst the best. I would steer clear of any of their chicken products, they're clearly an after thought and it shows. But let's be honest, if you came here for chicken you've already made a mistake from the get go. The portions are fair for the prices and the staff have always been friendly whenever I've been. It's clean and arguably the best chipper in d6 and certainly the best in rathmines.
Servers are more interested in their phones than service. Fish is over cooked. Sort your stuff out!  'Best chips and fish in Dublin' supposedly!
Very fresh fish good service and friendly staff

Most humans simply can't eat the volume of food that other burrito places give you. Pablo picante have smaller portions but way higher quality food. It's still very substantial but the city has got somewhat used to unnecessarily  gigantic burritos and burrito boxes. This was one of the original brands that brought the burrito wave and it has retained its high standards.

I really like the burrito bowls here. The food has so much more authenticity and depth to it than say Boojum or Tolteca. The meats are really well seasoned and always succulent. They also have a huge variety of spices sauces.
Always a good food experience. The food looks and tastes fresh and tasty as f**k. Good friendly staff and definitely my go to place for a burrito when in Dublin.

A really really tasty, well priced burrito.  Student deal: burrito + can of juice for €6.95 if you show student id.  Very roomy upstairs and very quick service.  The staff were kind enought to allow our group to leave suitcases at the restaurant for €1 each.
Some of the best burritos in town. Highly recommended. And if you haven't had the tortas, they're even better. Usually here at least once a week on my work break. Really good value as well.

Good hot and spicy wing's for Sunday lunch. My girl had Cesar salad. Both good i know as i finished her food. 3 pints of guiness in the beer garden people watching in temple  bar. Very happy. Oh there was a good musician on guitar doing a few great tracks. Very enjoyable.  Not loud just nice
Great place! Popped in for 2 hours on NYE and experienced great live music and fun. Very friendly and happy place!
Staff are lovely, food is nice, but a bit pricey for what it is.
By far the best place in Dublin from day time food to the best live music I have ever heard. Worth 're visiting just for the band. Simply brilliant.
Good place with live music

One of the best Italian restaurants in Dublin,  in my opinion, for many years. Recently, the restaurant has been refurbished and is now even cosier and more comfortable than it used to be. Also, the menu is very keenly priced and the early-bird menu is especially good value with the Bellini thrown in at no extra charge. The Italian staff are all totally professional, efficient, friendly and welcoming.

The staff was nice and friendly but the dish I had wasn't that great. The presentation was very good but taste and texture could have been better.

Looking at the other reviews, everyone seems to like so maybe it was just me. I will try something different next time.

For everyone else, go there and make up you own mind.

Visited this restaurant by chance on a quiet weeknight. Service was superb as was the food. Mushroom ravioli was the best we’ve ever had compared to many other similar restaurants (our favourite dish). Reasonable prices for the area with many specials. We will definitely be back!

Excellent food and excellent service, went here for a family get together and went for the set menu. Everyone raved about the starters and main courses. Excellent wine too. Slightly disappointed I didn't get the pizza as it looked amazing going to other tables. I'll definitely be back for the pizza, I might be changing my review to five stars. Keep up the excellent work folks! Viva Italia!

Best Italian restaurant in Dublin. 
Definitely our favourite place to have meals whether it's just a quick lunch or romantic dinner!!!
Highly recommended! 10/10

Great food, generous portions and a fair price. I have had duck, but 2/3 spiciness proved to be too much for me, 2 friends who were with me made better choices and their food was amazing.
Oh yeah, the food was ready in less than 5mins on a busy Saturday!

So bad. First point the delivery service is really terrible, couldn't find a building where the name is clearly readable and for helping the delivery we said all the time that the building is next to another restaurant where its name is with neon, how can you miss that?!
Second point, we've ordered a vegetarian food and surprise surprise there was meat, what if people have some allergies? Just let them die?!
We sent an email but didn't receive any answer so far. GREAT JOB!
Fresh tasty Thai. My go to Thai takeaway. The staff are polite and its handy after I do the gym to pick up from there. I always have the Tom Ka Gai and its delicious and low in calories. Keep it up.
Ordered food the day and it was very tasty. Had the beef chilli, it was nice and spicy with lots of flavour. Will order again soon! Oh and the delivery was prompt!

Gross, greasy and expensive. A friend and I ordered food to take home with us and for wok fried noodles at €12 without table service you’re setting very high expectations. As an asian with a thorough understanding of the costs involved in the ingredients €12 is extortionate. It’s equivalent price and quality to cheaper asian takeaways. Without prejudice I would say it intends to serve people who can’t cook even the most basic Asian dish at home because those who can will instantly recognise that this food is bland, small portions, average ingredient quality (lots of fatty meat) and way over priced. This place was popular many years ago when there weren’t as many Asian options, the world has moved on and this place needs to too.

One of the best meals I’ve had in Dublin and I’ve been living here over a year now. 
The pub downstairs was jammed! Great Friday evening post work buzz. Came upstairs and the restaurant was a bit quieter, nice ambient lighting. 
My parents had the FX Buckley burger, one tried the highland beef meat in their burger. The beef dripping chips with Parmesan shavings and truffle oil are amazing! Cooked to perfection.
I had the beef and Guinness pie with spring onion mash and creamed spinach with Parmesan. 10/10. 
Aoife our waitress was lovely and so was the other server. 
Great hearty Dublin food, best selection of side orders I’ve seen. And a great range of craft beers, wines, cocktails, the lot! Desserts looked awesome too. 
Will definitely be back.
Fantastic atmosphere. Recent refurbishment has been in keeping with the character and adds to the charm! Lovely staff and a great pint of Guinness.
if your looking for good food [ especially steaks] then this is the place to go. A little bit on the expensive side but worth every cent. Also serves a good pint of Guinness.
Loved it.. creamy pints of Guinness and then burger and chips. Really good time on a wet Sunday afternoon

Old school Victorian pub near Heuston Station. Nice period décor. Has two private areas or snugs at the ends of the bar. The only downside with this place is that it is hard to find space for a group of five or more due to the layout of the bat, and the fact that it immensely popular and generally crowded.
Inspiring 💫
Haven't been for a while but it was always very good.

I was charged with a mysterious "Donation to Alone" without my consent.

-- Seen the reply below from the owner. and this is my additional comment: 
My point is I'm sure it's a great initiative and it's for a great cause and I don't doubt that. However, I was not informed about this donation and it was not presented as an option for me. The waiter did not inform me about this when the bill came out and I only found out after the fact. As this was a business dinner, even though this was a small charge, it raised a flag when I tried reimburse my meal.

Extremely delicious. Tuna starter was absolutely amazing. Only downsides were service was nice but not close to
The level I expected or close to
Michelin star (empty wine glasses left after next wines were brought out and was standard care for a nice restaurant) All the food was incredible except the cheese plate was flat and nothing exciting especially for being an extra cost. Overall worth the trip but doesn’t come close to blowing your mind.

This amazing place should be on your 'must visit list' when in Dublin. the chef takes such pride in the taste  and presentation. The food is sophisticated without being in the least bit intimidating. Alexander was our host tonight. He couldn't have been more accommodating  even though the staff were bombarded by a large last-minute booking. We have followed this expert professional through three restaurants over ten years. We have spent many special nights in the care of his friendly and welcoming nature. Tonight also we met the owner of Bang. we didn't know it - the gentleman welcomed us as any professional would. no airs or graces. We only learned the man was the owner upon his departure from another guest at the table beside us. An obvious professional who possesses high level understanding of the importance of customer welcome and satisfaction. Also, he's an obvious high-level authority on correct wines and drinks. Food taste: 10/10, presentation, 10/10, drinks: 10/10, comfort and welcome 20/10... A perfect experience all round. Very much looking forward to our next visit.

We had an incredible meal. The octopus starter was amazing and we had the venison and duck breasts as mains and they were delicious. The service was excellent and everyone was very nice. I will definitely come back!

Professional chef designs all your 5 course menu and serves you by explaining what the dish is made of. Nice experience for first timers who hasn’t been to any fancy places like this. It is delicious as well
Lovely restaurant but to be honest the food was below average and the cost was above.I will not be in a hurry back.
Love the place. Always good
Very good restaurant would recommend nice. Staff very friendly
Excellent food and service.  Tables a bit crowded.
Good food, nice atmosphere and comprehensive wine list. Dublin 4 prices.
Average restaurant. Good carvery, good service, nothing super outstanding, but good if you just want a place to eat and relax!
Closed without warning on the Wednesday evening despite being told it would be open by the restaurant staff two days before.

Booked a table a month ahead for my daughter's First Holy Communion. My guests comprised of adults and kids. Welcomed with warmth and friendliness. The kids were attended well, crayons and coloring sheets as well as their own menus. Menu sheets with my daughter's name on it showed such personal touch. The food were presented beautifully, amazingly scruptious and well portioned. The Chef takes pride in the food and it showed. I had the Trout as main and it tasted delicious. For me personally this place will always have the best bread and butter pudding I've ever. The two staff who attended us (Jose and Saril) moved efficiently and anticipated their guests needs. Everyone went home satisfied and with a happy full tummy! Thank you so much for making my daughter's evening a memorable one.
A good choice of carvery foods. Friendly staff. Nice surroundings. Large portions. Deserts/starters  are limited. Worth a visit at lunchtime.

Continues as a quality restaurant with efficient table attention. Our group of 6 or 7 continue to lunch in UNICORN every 6 weeks. No complaints - food with set menu or otherwise is nicely presented and appreciated though secondary to our conversation. House wine is very acceptable.  We have tried many in the vicinity and this suits us best.
Amazing service, great food selection and wonderful flavors. Wine selection was very representative of Italy, and everything we had tasted fabulous. Definitely a "Highly Recommend"!

When I first read the menu upon sitting down at this restaurant, one thought came to mind - Here, if nowhere else, the boom is back. With "nibbles" and sides all at €6 and main pasta courses starting at 17 for a tiny portion, its safe to say the prices here are outrageous.
I then decided to curb my thoughts and give them the benefit of the doubt. The food must justify the price, methinks. Well. Methought wrong. My brother and I ordered the artichoke ravioli as we are vegetarian and were shocked at how bland it was. 5/6 large pieces of ravioli with some white sauce and artichokes on top, that were almost completely tasteless, for 17 euro? Even the size of the portion paled in comparison to the meat dishes. It was extremely disappointing when one considers how easy it is to make nice Italian veggie food with pesto, tomatoes, veg etc. I cannot speak for how the other dishes or meat tastes but I don't think I will be taking out a mortgage so I can return again. I must say the only redeeming quality was the service. We were served extremely quickly and the waiters were lovely. However, what sort of italian restaurant doesn't have garlic bread, if nothing else?
Great food and service. Name a bit misleading though, I imagined decor to be something more special... Typical small restaurant decor. Nice and cosy though.

Delicious starter. Bouillabaise was tastey but had tomatoes in the sauce....optional???
Maybe I should have tried some of the Pasta dishes on the menu instead.
Dover Sole was dry. 
Lovely staff gave us a table for 2 in the corner even though we hadn't made a reservation.
